n hagiographic narrative, including gender, power, violence and history; and, finally, shows how hagiographic themessurvived the Reformation. Overall it offers both information for those coming to the genre for the first time, and points forward to new trends in research. Dr SARAH SALIH is a Lecturer in English at the University of East Anglia. Contributors: SAMANTHA RICHES, MARY BETH LONG, CLAIRE M. WATERS, ROBERT MILLS, ANKE BERNAU, KATHERINE J. LEWIS, MATTHEW WOODCOCK  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian hagiography. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aMiddle English hagiography.  aReformation.  aSaints' Life.  agender.  ahistory.  amedieval England.  apower.  areligious literature.  aviolence.1 aBernau, Anke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Katherine J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Katherine J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, Mary Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiches, Samantha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalih, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalih, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWaters, Claire M, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaters, Claire M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWoodcock, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.151